This shroud takes an additional 40x10mm cooling fan and ejects cool air onto the nozzle and extruded filament. I found that if I printed very fine vertical elements the residual heat warped and melted the model. I also made a thin gasket using thick cardboard to help seal the gap between the fan and the shroud. You could also use that thin plastic/polystyrene packing stuff that comes with disk drives and the like.

It was designed for the Mk8 extruder fitted to a Geeetech Aluminum (Prusa i3 clone).

This version has a mounting hole for a mini-switch that allows you to turn the fan on & off as required. In order to power the fan you should take a 12v source from either your power supply/motherboard or tap into the existing fan supply. I took mine from the "Extruder 2 fan" socket. Disclaimer: I cannot be held responsible if you wire it incorrectly etc. etc.

Print the two parts and glue with Super-glue etc. Line up carefully - there are no locating pegs/lugs.

A desktop ball bearing spool holder for 3D printers that can quickly adjust to hold different spool widths.  
I needed a spool holder for my Printrbot Simple so I created this from my replicator1 version.  
Different width spools can be used by just moving the inner support to a different slot.  
The spool widths currently supported are from about 40mm wide to about 85mm wide. The supported spool widths can be changed in the OpenSCAD source code.

Parts:
  • Printed parts from both STL files.
  • 4 #608 skate bearings.
  • 14 #1 x 3/8 Button head servo hold down screws. You can get these from J&R Hobby Hardware at: http://www.jrhobbyhardware.com/shop/index.php?main_page=index&cPath=108_109
    • Instructions:

  • Print both STL files at a .25mm Layer height, 25% infill, with 2 extra shells. Both ABS and PLA work, but I prefer the PLA because it's stiffer.

    Slide the 4 bearings onto the posts.

    Use 4 screws to attach the bearing keeper disks.

    Put the mounting bracket into the slot in the top of the tall bracket. (It goes on the other side from the bearings) It's a tight fit, you may have to sand it a bit. It goes with the long side facing up as show in the picture. The mounting bracket should go in until it's flush with the other side of the tall bracket.

    Use 6 screws to mount the arms to the tall bracket. They go with the slots facing in.

    Use 4 screws to mount the end plate (The part without bearings) to the end of the arms.

    Put the spool holder into the Replicator1. It goes in just tlike the stock holder.

    Drop the inside bearing bracket into the correct slot for the spool you have. Spools from about 40mm to 75mm are supported. The bracket goes with the notches in the tabs on the bottom. It should sit flush with the top of the arm.

    Enjoy!

    • Customizing:
    You can change the spool widths by updating the array variable SpoolWid. Just make sure the first one is the biggest and the last one is the smallest. You can add more spool widths as well, just make sure there is at least 3 to 4 mm between them so the spaces between the slots don't get too small. Also, change the variable SpoolCnt to the number of spool widths you have. To print all the parts you need to generate two STL files. Changing the variable DoArms from 0 to 1 selects which set of parts will be drawn. There are many other parameters that can be adjusted. Please see the source code.

title: Tevo Tarantula Cable hiding Extruder mount

description.text:
I really hate looking at loose cables, so I made this extrudermount to make it possible to tuck away all the cables I'd running along the bowden tube. I designed it for my Tevo Tarantula with standard extruder but I guess it fits the other Tarantula extruders and alot of other printers aswell.
The mount also has a slot on the left side so that you're able to turn your motor around, have its connector pointing towards the frame and hide the cable from that aswell.

Would really like some feedback on this as it's the first thing i'm uploading!

Here's a remix of thingirobs z-bracket which I designed to go along with this extruder mount:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2725363

4x m4 T-nuts (already on standard mount)
4x m4x10 socket screws (already on standard mount)
Tube/Spiral/Tape to wrap cables

Run all cables (such as hotend, thermistor, endstop, coolingfans) along the bowden tube. Wrap everything in some tubing/spiral/tape. When you get to the extruder, separate the bowden tube from the cables. Put the tube in the extruder as usual and put the cables behind the mount.
At the bottom of the mount, the cables are supposed to come out inside the slots of the 2040 aluminum, where they can easily be covered up.
Since the cableconnectors are hard to feed through the mount, I suggest that you first put the cables inside the mount and then bolt it to the frame.

Same mounting parts as you would've used on thingirobs original design
Make sure you use sucket head bolts, at least for the holes where the cover sits on top. Otherwise you won't be able to get the cover in place

If you're using my modified bracket:
Just install the bracket as you would've done with thingirobs original version. Then take the cables who comes down inside the slots of the 2040 aluminum, Put them along the top of the bracket and then into the middle and down the hole you've drilled in whatever your printer's standing on. When your cables are in place, take the cover and push it onto the heads of the socket bolts holding the bracket.

If you're using thingirobs original bracket:
Start of by drilling a hole in the base of the bracket. Center it between the two right rows of bolts on the front side of the bracket and put it as close to the vertical part as possible.
Run the cables along the top of the bracket, down between the bolts and throught the hole you just drilled. Then push the thicker version of the cover onto the socket bolt heads to cover the cables.

description.text:
Snap Linkage Bars

I have always liked linkage structures, simple to construct but fascinating to play with in math or mechanics. All children should have some experience with some linkages before entering the world of abstract geometry, I think. They provide numerous opportunities for children to wonder about the mathematics of geometry and movements. With 3D design, it is getting easier and more flexible. I have designed these pieces with K-12 teachers and students in mind. They are fairly easy to assemble or disassemble for open-ended explorations.

The center-to-center distance is 40mm. There are two types of links or bars and four types of pins, allowing for a variety of construction. Whenever you need to fix a point (e.g., with a nail of diameter about 3.5mm), you should use a hollow pin. If you need to connect three bars (layers), you need use a three-layer pin. Sometimes you may need a spacer to align the bars in space, too. There are numerous possibilities. Please print a bunch and give them to your kids. Yes, you could insert a regular pencil in the handle ring or a ballpoint pen (diameter < 3.5 mm) in a hollow pin and play with drawing!

Warning: As always, please take some time to educate young children not to put small parts in their mouth. Have fun making connections.

References:

  1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linkage_(mechanical)
  2. Cundy, H. M., & Rollett, A. P. (1961). Mathematical models (2nd ed.). London, UK: Oxford University Press.

title: Flying Tourbillon Model V (Daniels Double Independant Wheel Remontoir Escapement)

description.text:
I had been meaning to return to the Daniels Double Escapement for a while. Here it is spinning merrily away at 4rpm/14400bph:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3_5mmGTDFHM

In my view, it is the most aesthetically pleasing watch escapement. As described previously:

"...This is a model watch escapement based on a design by George Daniels based on the natural escapement concept by Breguet as ingeniously utilized by Derek Pratt (I could go on). It couples the benefits of the Swiss lever with those of the detent escapement while attempting to eliminate each designs' weaknesses. Of course the potential added efficiency and accuracy is almost wholly negated by the added mechanical complexity. Even so, I find its visual symmetry coupled with its intentionally asymmetric tick more appealing. The latter quality necessitates a...."

...remontoir. to decouple the escape wheels from each other as the carriage rotates. The alternative is to have two separate power trains as George Daniels did in his watches, but that is difficult to incorporate into a tourbillon, so I stuck with the remontoirs. This time around because it is hand powered, I eliminated the forks.

I originally intended to power this design off of a weighted ball chain, but this escapement requires much more power. This is somewhat counterintuitive since it relies on radial thrust rather than sliding action as in the Swiss Lever. The greater mass of the carriage, the inertial of two escape wheels, and the double unlocking action, however, more than make up for the energy saved. In an actual watch, that may not be the case especially if there are two power trains independently driving each escape wheel. I may adapt the hub piece to incorporate the spring motor I designed for my Dual Ulysse model.

Assembly notes:

  • All shafts are 2mm
  • Requires one 608 bearing (22x8x7)
  • Print two of the spokes part and print two escape wheels (one mirrored)
  • The pallets (both impulse and locking) are slightly oversized and must be sanded down to perfect fit.
  • The top frame kind of looks like some sort of Satanic goat head emblem
  • Add grub screws to the balance wheel to calibrate

Printing Instructions:
Printed at 0.15mm with stock .4 nozzle on a Prusa i3 MK2 using a combination of transparent PLA (GizmoDorks), 3dk.berlin "rotmetallic" metallic red PLA, Hatchbox silver PLA, and generic white PLA.

Standard PLA temp (210/50) and supports for some parts including the body, base, hemisphere, shoulders, and arms.

White parts: Base, Shoulders, and Hands
Silver parts: Arms, Motor detail, and Mouth
Red parts: Body, Motor, Neck, and Hat
Clear parts: Hemi (x2)

Note: If you have problems printing any of the parts sliced in Slic3r, try using Cura or another slicer instead.

Post-printing & Assembly
  1. Use glue to assemble 2 hemispheres into a globe, glue that to the top of the Neck piece, then glue the Hat to the top of the head globe.
  2. Embed a knurled M3 nut in hole at base of Neck piece by melting it into the plastic with a soldering iron or 3d pen.
  3. Using Loctite or glue, thread and lock an M3 threaded rod into the neck.
  4. Glue and insert a 1.75mm piece of scrap filament into each shoulder piece with filament curved down.
  5. Slide arm coil pieces up arm filament and glue to shoulder.
  6. Snip filament fragment to just under the arm coil, then glue and filament end into hand.
  7. Glue shoulders, Base, and Motor to the Body.
  8. Glue Motor detail to motor.
  9. Pass the M3 threaded rod that is attached to the Neck through the Body and Base.
  10. Use a washer and M3 nuts to hold the thread to the base, but with enough slack to allow the rod to turn freely. This will allow the head to rotate just like the full sized Tom Servo via turning the rod.
  11. Cut rod length to just above the Base bottom to allow Servo to be placed on surfaces.
  12. Celebrate by riffing movies with your new friend.

Designs modified in Meshmixer, 3D Builder, and ADSK Fusion 360.

Modifications:

  1. hollowed the head globe hemispheres to make them more transparent than original.
  2. Hollowed base hoverskirt to allow head control rod to be operated from under the model.
  3. Increased scale of neck, globe, hat, and mouth to closer approximation of actual Tom Servo.
  4. Fixed some other minor issues with parts.

title: micro to nano sim card cutter jig template

description.text:
Two times I've typed up long comprehensive instructions only to get "Token Expired" when I hit save......

TL;DR:

  • the micro SIM should have the contacts facing up (visible), and roughly aligning up with the embossed rectangle in the slot.
  • put the micro SIM in each slot, starting at "1" and trim off anything sticking out.
  • use a sharp blade, scissors, clippers, whatever.

I like to put the SIM in place then turn the jig over and cut it on a flat surface.

And however you use it, please please please, be careful when cutting and avoid injuring yourself/fingers/bits/etc.

Note, this was created using size information from random websites and measurements of SIMs I had on hand. I didn't use the official standard since I didn't find a free copy. So results may deviate from the official sizes.

If your SIM breaks while you use this device to trim it, that is unfortunately your problem. However, if this happens, please let me know, perhaps it will lead some to improvements.

use: RoundedCube_hull.scad

  • Add module at beginning of code.
  • Use rCube(x, y, z, radius, resolution); to make cube/box.

title: P3 Steel Y Bed Tensioner Holder Mount GT2 1.75mm steel cord belt

description.text:
P3 Steel Y Bed belt tensioner and Y Bed belt mount. The tensioner should work for many belt types .. but the Y bed mount is sized specifically for the thicker 1.75m thick GT2 belt with steel cording. This type belt requires running very high belt tension, system must be designed to handle those loads.

Belt tensioner is designed in 2 pieces, to reduce tensile loads on print layers (weak direction). Note the spacer that is used on each end of the 5mm diameter by 22mm long axle shaft. 3 Housing screws at M3x25 .... 2 Tensioning screws at M3x25 or M3x30. Standard M3 nuts are inserted. Note: every tensioner or Y idler mount, including the P3 Steel part .. is NOT aligned to the Y motor centerline .. this tensioner I have designed is correctly centered with the motor, so the belt runs parallel to the Y bed and is evenly spaced over the entire length. Pulley used is a GT2 20 tooth pulley with internal 5mm ID ball bearings.

Y Bed Belt mount is for use with Thick 1.75mm GT2 steel corded belting, mounted on 20 tooth pulleys. For a standard P3 Steel a 15mm spaced will be required (I have an extended bed with Open Beam 15mm stock, which this part screws to). This belt holder incorporates a belt damper shoe to reduced vibration in the lower return portion of the belt.

description.text: -UPDATE: This (while still playable) is an outdated Pocket-Tactics design. For current sets and rules, go here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:586240 Introducing Pocket-Tactics! A fast-paced, modular strategy board game that all fits in a tiny bag. Still not sure what we'll do with this little game, though I'd like to make it free to print and play to my fellow makers. My nerdsmen and I have been having a blast with it these last few days. If anyone ends up printing one of these let me know how it plays, I'd love to get some feedback. Reporting any typos/mistakes in the rules would be greatly appreciated as well. We'll be updating the progress of the game and provide expanded rules on our blog, so be sure and check us out there as well http://illgottengames.blogspot.com/ All of the pieces were designed using Tinkercad. https://tinkercad.com/users/bHIdLANxoGl-arian-croft

Each piece was printed on my Makerbot Replicator at a .10 layer height with 10% infill. I printed them all one piece at a time, though you can feel free to try and print bricks of them. I had trouble doing so and it was probably due to my calibration. All in all, the set takes about 9 hours to print, give or take. So, for the core set as I've designed it, you'll need the following (and I've included the colors you should paint things, though this is only a suggestion): -3 Conscripts (tan) -2 Archers (tan) -2 Spearmen (tan) -2 Swordsmen (tan) -1 Shieldmaiden (tan) -1 Fire Mage (tan) -3 Beastfolk Stalkers (dark green) -2 Beastfolk Marauders (dark green) -2 Beastfolk Juggernauts (dark green) -2 Forest Witches (dark green) -1 Cursed Ranger (dark green) -1 Druid (dark green) -1 Caer (tan) -1 Druid's Circle (dark green) -2 Village Tiles (tan) -3 Water Tiles (blue) -4 Hills Tiles (light green) -4 Field Tiles (yellow) -7 Forest Tiles (dark green) You'll also need a grip of six-sided dice (6 for each player) and it helps immensely if half of them are a different color. The rules are in super-beta mode (just finished writing them last night) so expect typos and confusion, but throw me some feedback and I can answer questions/clean up the document as we go. -Big props to our tech editor, John Peden ([email protected]) for this new, squeaky clean rules sheet

description.text:
Give your Roomba a Rhino horn!

I needed something to keep my Roomba 880 from getting stuck under the radiator all the time. Tried one of the stoppers I found here on thingiverse, but it was interfering with the IR sensor on the top.

So I took inspiration from that and designed a Rhino horn for my Roomba that I stuck onto it using a 3M command strip. As far as I know, it should work for all Roomba models as the top IR sensor size is the same for all of them. If not, it should be fairly easy to scale it in your choice of slicer.

This is a simple recursive snowflake in BlocksCAD. You can customize the parameters by going to the project page and choosing "Create my own".

The basic shape is done by drawing a line, and then doing recursion for six scaled-down and rotated/translated shapes. The result is one sixth of the 2D image, which is then extruded and rotated six times in a loop, as per Challenge directions.

To print, choose one of the ones with thicker interior walls. I used a razor to help remove the delicate snowflake from the bed. It had some threads which actually helped keep it together. Transparent white PLA made it look very much like a snowflake.

The Customizer here is made by exporting the BlocksCAD file to OpenSCAD, and then moving the variables to the top of the file.

December 22, 2017: Added an adjusted version where the inner segments are thicker, which makes the snowflake more durable when printed.

description.text:
On my Prusa i3 clone the loom tube that holds the cable for the hotbed is quite stiff. I was worried that the connection will brake when the bed is moving.

2 x M3x20 Socket Cap Screws (ISO 912)
2 x M3 Nuts

I designed two version of the loom tube fixation, one where the tube is perpendicular to the hotbed (shown in the pictures) and one with an angle of 20 degree.

Place the lower part first below your bed and fixate the loom with the cable tie. Don't fully tighten the cable tie yet. Add the upper parts and fixate the complete block by tightening the M3 screw. Last tighten the cable tie to fixate the loom tube.

description.text:
This is an 8-bit Princess Peach - as in original Super Mario Bros., "our princess is in another castle" pre-blonde Princess Peach - hanging ornament made specifically for multi-extruder printers (though I have included a one-piece model for single-extruder machines). It's perfect for the rear-view mirror, Christmas tree, etc.

Please be aware that - though some post-printing assembly is required - the fully colourized version of this model was not designed to be printed in pieces on a single-extruder machine and assembled afterwards. Use peach_onepiece.stl to get everything at once in a single colour.

The print in the cover photo was done on a quad extruder Prusa i3 MK2 MMU as follows:

Step 1:

  • peach_black.stl black PLA (extruder 1)
  • peach_white.stl white PLA (extruder 2)
  • peach_flesh.stl pale flesh PLA (extruder 3)
  • peach_red.stl red PLA (extruder 4)

Step 2:

  • peach_gold.stl gold PLA (extruder 1)

Assembly:
Because I used more colours than I have extruders, some post-printing assembly is required. After printing the crown separately, simple glue it into the crown-shaped hole in the black backplate. I have made the hole in the backplate slightly bigger than the crown, so everything should fit together quite easily.

For those of you who have fewer extruders (or who like painting a lot more than I do), I have included peach_onepiece.stl, which can be used to print everything at once in a single colour/material, no post-printing assembly required.

When printed at 100% size, the ornament measures approximately 45mm x 78mm.

Happy printing!

title: Radial Fan Tornado dual 5015 parts cooler with interchangeable, customizable ducts and integrated HSF shroud (FLSun i3 with e3d v6)

description.text:
Tired of the edges of overhangs curling and strands sagging off the bottoms of bridges?
Looking for extreme, tuneable cooling, with double the cooling potential of the Radial Fan Fang?

I really liked supasorn's simple dual-blower cooler design, and when he made it modular with interchangeable ducts I had to adapt it to the FLSun i3. Instead of a separate over-the-fan bolt-on, I stuck the ducts to the sides of my v6 HSF Shroud (I have been thinking about integrating the shrouds in to the RFF for a while). This made it a little harder to print, but the installation is much cleaner, and with a pair of new 5015s that push some actual CFM this thing really blows (I didn't realize how badly the original blower fan performed until I replaced it)! Enjoy!

It is designed to be used with the e3d v6 or clone hotend upgrade (using BFAL's lowering holder), 40mm heatsink fan, and a pair of 5015 (12V ~.15A) blower fans.

Wider ducts are better for preventing warping on larger parts, and more focused ducts are better for smaller parts, overhangs, and bridges (for more details read Desi Quintans' http://www.desiquintans.com/coolingtests and http://www.desiquintans.com/coolingtests2).

You can swap from wide-angle ducts to focused cooling in seconds, even run a combination of the two, and make sure to check out the original design (which should be linked on the left there) for instructions on how to modify the ducts to your needs using Fusion 360 and the included file.

Some kind of heater block and bed insulation is recommended to help out your heaters.

Comes a little close to the z-carriage blocks so i gave it a few mm clearance, let me know if you have any fitment issues.

e3d V5 version based on the lo-pro shroud (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2243045) coming soon (tho this would probably work if you get creative and do a little trimming).

Looking to keep it simple and stick with just one blower? Check out my Radial Fan Fang remix, adapted for the FLSun i3 with either the original v5 clone, or v6 hotend: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2243045

title: Remix of Star Farer from Star Citizens

description.text:
Happy Christmas,

i´ve got a remix of the Star Farer from Star Citizens. As always i made some changes to the original (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2702291):

  • Size: Scaled up from 20 cm to about 62 cm
  • Changed the weapons for others with more details
  • Sliced the complete spaceship new. I don´t know why the builders take everytime the smallest joints for slicing. Horrible to glue so i set new part sizes.
  • Made it hollow
  • Added door
  • Fuel Tank and Cargo are screwed to plate with 3 mm screws.
  • Complete LED Cutouts build in
  • Made complete new pilots with more details and space for LED´s
  • Attached a second foldable wing for better stability in flight. Screwed to wing with 3 mm Screws.
  • The LED in the Jet Engine have to be build in before glueing it together and then attach it to the body. Hole is cut in the midlle part for the power cable.
  • Attached the movable legs from the spider tank. Choose what version you want: With or without LED.
  • You have to mirror the needed body parts for the other side. If you have problems contact me, then i can check/make missing parts if needed. But shouldn´t be a problem when you orientate and mirror in the correct axis in the slicer.

I am in print at the moment and the model is so heavy that the legs will not hold the weight when standing. I will glue them permanently in.

Schöne Weihnachten,

habe euch ein Remix von der Star Farer aus Star Citizens gemacht. Wie immer habe ich einige Sachen zum besseren abgeändert:

  • Größe: Von 20 cm auf ca. 62 cm
  • Die Waffen gegen "schönere" ausgetauscht mit mehr details und drehbar. Im Original sind alle Waffen fest montiert. Nach dem drucken etwas ausdremeln um ggf. passenden Freilauf/Widerstand zu bekommen. Werden nur aufgesteckt.
  • Das gesamte Schiff habe ich neu gesliced nach dem Upscaling. Ich verstehe nicht warum die Designer im original immer die schwächsten Stellen als Slice/Klebepunkte nehmen. Ist ein graus das alles so zu kleben. Daher neu gesliced.
  • Innen hohl gemacht
  • Tür ergänzt auf der Unterseite damit Licht raus kann bzw. Zugang möglich
  • Sprittank und Ladung werden mit 3 mm Schrauben an der Trägerplatte befestigt und dann unten ran geklebt. Ist einfacher und Ihr könnt zwischen 1-4x Ladung anbringen bzw. 1-2 Sprittanks. Sind gesliced, also ausdrucken und zusammen kleben.
  • Komplette LED Cutouts am/im gesamten Schiff
  • Komplett neue Piloten gemacht, da die Marines hier nicht passen und zudem mit viel mehr Details. LED Aussparungen für Bildschirmbeleuchtung und so vorhanden samt Aussparungen um Kabel verlegen zu können.
  • Am hinteren Flügel einen weiteren ausklappbaren "Air Wing" ergänzt. Idee ist von Babylon 5 mit den neuen Kampffliegern, die auch ausklappbare Flügel hatten zwecks Atmosphären Flug. In der Realität würde das Schiff nämlich niemals ohne Zusatzflügel fliegen können, sieht aber auch gut aus.
  • Die LED´s in den äußeren Bereichen als erstes einbauen bevor ihr zusammen klebt. Sonst kommt Ihr nicht mehr innen ran. Und danach auch noch die Kabel checken, denn hier kommt Ihr unter Umständen später auch nicht mehr ran. Also erst die eine Hälfte drucken und Kabelwege/LED checken und Prinzip: Von außen nach Innen.
  • Die beweglichen Beine vom Spider Tank (eines der letzten Remixe) ergänzt. Sind beweglich und natürlich sind beide Versionen der Beine enthalten: Mit oder ohne LED Cutouts. Entscheidet selbst, aber ich empfehle mit LED Cutouts.
  • Die fehlenden Bodyparts müsst Ihr euch in Cura oder eurem 3D Programm spiegeln. Wenn Ihr Probleme habt einfach kontaktieren, ich schaue dann dass ich das fehlende Teil erstelle/ hoch lade. Sollte aber kein Problem sein, wenn Ihr euch an der richtigen Spiegelachse ausrichtet.

Bin momentan am Druck und das Modell wird so schwer, dass können die Beine im beweglichen Zustand nicht halten. Werde daher die Beine permant fest kleben. Sollte dann eigentlich halten.

Quellen/Sources:
Star Farer original: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2702291
Pilot (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1761697)
Legs and weapons from my last remixes

Notes:
  • Print the Pilots and Guns in 0,1 mm and with MORE infill than 20% for better details and stability.
  • Print the legs with 0,1 mm / 80% infill or more cause of the weight of the model and details of the legs. Otherwise they can brake easily.
  • Druckt die Piloten und die Waffen mit 0,1 mm und mehr als 20% Infill für bessere Details und mehr Stabilität beim auslösen der Stützen vom Druck.
  • Druckt die Beine mit 0,1 mm /80%-100% Infill wegen besserer Details und dem Gewicht (ca. 1,5 kg auf 4 Beine verteilt). Sonst brechen die Beine mit Sicherheit recht schnell ab. Vorsichtig dremeln nach dem Druck um leichte Freigängigkeit zu haben wie Ihr es wollt. Brecht euch nicht den Pin im Loch ab sonst könnt Ihr ausbohren.

comments.text:
The two dome halves are made with white FrostLite plastic. I think its usually used over fluorescent lights. Its perfect at diffusing light, but is a pain in the ass to cut. Its very brittle. I first heat the oven to 350 and use a MDF frame to hold the sheet of plastic. I staple the plastic to the frame and put it in the oven. Once the plastic starts to droop in the oven I quickly pull it out and lay it over a vacuum form of a dome shape. The dome shape was once a cool modern lamp shade that I absconded with to make the ufo lamp, I turn on the shop vac I have hooked to a vacuum table and it sucks the hot sheet down over the dome. It cools quickly and voila! you have a cool dome shaped piece of plastic with a bunch of flashing that needs to be removed. I use a pair of heavy duty scissors to cut off some of the plastic and use a 3M deburring wheel on a grinder to finely shape the final edge of the plastic. It took me over a year of failed experiments to figure out how to cut and shape the plastic.
It has taken me another year to sort out the design that hopefully doesnt crack the plastic dome. Hopefully, I have figured it out. I will keep you posted.

A redesign / overhaul of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1243891 to fit the Geetech Aluminum Prusa i3 and it's default MK8 extruder.

It doesn't make too much of a wind on the extruder (more like a breeze, it's barely noticeable), as the standard radial fan can't put out a lot of pressure.
But the airflow is there, and I'm now having success printing thin profiles in ABS that would be piles of molten plastic otherwise.

I recommend printing the first layer without it to improve adhesion, then after the first few layers installing it before the thinner sections are printed. It can be installed or removed while the print is running or paused, no screws required (just get it in between the wires, and slide it over the fan and heat sink).
Or just leave it there and unplug the fan to turn it off temporarily, then turn it back on afterwards (don't forget this! or your Z-stepper will get very hot). This is my preferred method for small objects.

The original and available remixes didn't fit my printer (the duct nozzle didn't line up w/ the extruder, etc) and the available files were hard to edit, so I set about making my own model using the same idea.

title: Image To Gcode Converter for RepRap 3D Printer / Laser Engraver / Plotter

description.text:
Hi there!
This is a simply standalone programm that converts any picture to Gcode for RepRap 3D Printers. It's pretty simple and has usefull features, that makes engraving / plotting on your 3D Printer easyer!

Download the actual version: https://mega.nz/#!AwsjTSoa!kmYxHlAmc2Q0DSnstGLCvClsFyBiBXD4wxjspSpe-N8

• PWM mode for engraving images with grayscale
  • smart and fast moves due to intelligent algorithm
  • white balance adjustment and inverting the image with preview
  • custom ON / OFF commands allow you to use this programm with different types of 3D
    printers / laser engravers and plotters
  • your custom start- and end- GCode for better control
  • custom start position
  • 3 save slots allow you to save 3 different settings
  • autosave all parameters on exit and autoload on restart

How to use it? Just follow this steps:

  • drag and drop your image in the picture window
  • adjust the White Offset with the trackbar or just click on the brightest point of the image.
    This color value will be burned with the minimal laser power that you can set. Brighter
    colors will be passed
  • set minimal and maximal laser power values
  • set feedrate speed (speed for burning moves) and travel speed for non-burning moves (with this speed laser moves on white areas of the image)
  • set resolution. Smaller resolution gives more detailed results, but more engraving time.
    Just test and find the right value for you!
  • set GCode commands for turning on and off your laser. If your laser is attached to FAN pin
    D9 (on Ramps 1.4) then just type "M106" for ON-command and "M107" for OFF-command.
    If you connected your laser to another IO pin, then use "M42 Px" for ON command and
    "M42 Px S0" for laser OFF command (x ist the laser pin)
  • set the output result size of your image. Here you can set the width or the height. The
    proportional scale factor is the same as by original image.
  • set start coordinates. X and Y are the left lower corner of the image. Z is the distance
    between the laser and focused point
  • write your own custom start / end GCode if needed.
  • if you want to engrave your picture without grayscale (only black and white - best for pcb) check "1-Bit Color" Checkbox and adjust the white offset value.
